    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, opportunity cost, the ever-present specter in the land of economics. Imagine a company, let's call it GoblinTech, standing at a crossroads. On one path, they can invest in shiny new factory machines, which would increase their production capacity. On the other, they could pour their gold into marketing, spreading the word about their wares far and wide. The opportunity cost here is the treasure they won't be able to spend on the other path. If they choose the machines, they miss out on the potential sales from marketing. Conversely, if they choose marketing, they forgo the increased production that the machines would have provided. It's a classic case of choosing one goblin's treasure over another, and the lost treasure is the opportunity cost.",
