      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! Let's strip away the goblin metaphors and focus on the numbers. If GoblinTech foregoes a marketing campaign that could have generated $50,000 in revenue, and instead they choose to purchase factory machines that are expected to increase revenue by $70,000, the opportunity cost of choosing the machines over marketing is the $50,000 they could have earned from the marketing campaign. \n\nIn your assignment, you would write this down as follows:\n\nOpportunity Cost = Potential Revenue from Foregone Option - Actual Revenue from Chosen Option\n\nIn this case:\n\nOpportunity Cost = $50,000 (Marketing) - $70,000 (Machines) = -$20,000\n\nThe negative sign indicates that GoblinTech actually made a better financial decision by choosing the machines, as they gained an additional $20,000 compared to what they would have gained from marketing. However, it's important to note that the opportunity cost is still $50,000, which is the revenue they sacrificed by not choosing the marketing option.",
